2 create_beautiful_radarchart function

#borrowed from: https://www.datanovia.com/en/blog/beautiful-radar-chart-in-r-using-fmsb-and-ggplot-packages/
create_beautiful_radarchart <- function(data, color = "#00AFBB", 
                                        vlabels = colnames(data), vlcex = 0.7,
                                        caxislabels = NULL, title = NULL, ...){
  radarchart(
    data, axistype = 1,
    # Customize the polygon
    pcol = color, pfcol = scales::alpha(color, 0.5), plwd = 2, plty = 1,
    # Customize the grid
    cglcol = "grey", cglty = 1, cglwd = 0.8,
    # Customize the axis
    axislabcol = "grey", 
    # Variable labels
    vlcex = vlcex, vlabels = vlabels,
    caxislabels = caxislabels, title = title, ...
  )
}

3 Prosody

3.1 Reading the data

dfVarImp <- read_csv("varImpShort.csv")[-1]
df <- read.csv("ResultsFitsPros_No_Corr.csv")

3.2 Subset and manipulation

dfVarImp_top <- dfVarImp %>% 
  filter(Grouping == "Prosody") %>% 
  filter(pvalue <= 0.1) %>% 
  select(-c(file, domain, pvalue, Comparison, Grouping)) %>% 
  group_by(correlate) %>%
  summarise(importanceMax = max(importance)) %>% # We compute the maximum importance of each variable to allow for sorting the data by the maximum importance score
  arrange(desc(importanceMax)) %>%
  pivot_longer(-correlate) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from=correlate, values_from=value) %>% 
  select(-name)

dfVarImp_top
dfSubset <- df %>% 
  dplyr::select(Model, SCD_Coefficient, naMCI_Coefficient, 
         aMCI_Coefficient, pAD_Coefficient) %>% 
  mutate(Model = factor(Model),
         Max = 2,
         Min = -2,
         HC_Coefficient = 0) %>% 
  relocate(Max, .after = Model) %>% 
  relocate(Min, .after = Max) %>% 
  relocate(HC_Coefficient, .after = Min) 
names(dfSubset) = gsub(pattern = "_Coefficient", 
                       replacement = "", 
                       x = names(dfSubset))

dfSubset
dfSubset2 <- data.frame(t(dfSubset[-1]))
colnames(dfSubset2) <- dfSubset[, 1]
names(dfSubset2) = gsub(pattern = ".mdl", 
                        replacement = "", 
                        x = names(dfSubset2))
dfSubset2
dfSubset2 <- dfSubset2 %>% 
  rename(TotInternuclDur = TotNuclDurInter,
         NrofSafe = NSafe)
#dfSubset2 <- dfSubset2 %>% 
  #rownames_to_column("Group")


dfSubset2 <- dfSubset2 %>% 
  select(any_of(names(dfVarImp_top)))

dfSubset2

3.3 Plots

3.3.1 Global

# Reduce plot margin using par()
op <- par(mar = c(1, 2, 2, 2))
par(mfrow = c(1,1))

# Create the radar charts
create_beautiful_radarchart(
  data = dfSubset2, caxislabels = c(-2, -1, 0, 1, 2),
  color = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07", "#B58526", "yellow")
)
# Add an horizontal legend
legend(
  x = "bottom", legend = rownames(dfSubset2[-c(1,2),]), horiz = TRUE,
  bty = "n", pch = 20 , 
  col = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07", "#B58526", "yellow"),
  text.col = "black", cex = 1, pt.cex = 1.5
)
par(op)

3.3.2 By group

# Define colors and titles
colors <- c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07", "#B58526", "yellow")
titles <- c("HC", "SCD", "nMCI", "aMCI", "pAD")

# Reduce plot margin using par()
# Split the screen in 3 parts
op <- par(mar = c(1, 1, 1, 1))
par(mfrow = c(3,2))

# Create the radar chart
for(i in 1:5){
  create_beautiful_radarchart(
    data = dfSubset2[c(1, 2, i+2), ], caxislabels = c(-2, -1, 0, 1, 2),
    color = colors[i], title = titles[i]
  )
}
par(op)

dfSubset3 <- dfSubset2[-c(1,2),]
dfSubset3
library(scales)
df_scaled <- round(apply(dfSubset3, 2, scales::rescale), 2)
df_scaled <- as.data.frame(df_scaled)
head(df_scaled, 8)

# Variables summary
# Get the minimum and the max of every column  
col_max <- apply(df_scaled, 2, max)
col_min <- apply(df_scaled, 2, min)
# Assign average as HC group
col_mean <- rowwise(df_scaled[1,]) %>% 
           group_split() %>%  map(~pivot_longer(.x, 
                                    cols=everything()) %>%  
                                      deframe()) %>% 
  unlist()
# Put together the summary of columns
col_summary <- t(data.frame(Max = col_max, Min = col_min, Average = col_mean))


# Bind variables summary to the data
df_scaled2 <- as.data.frame(rbind(col_summary, df_scaled[-1,]))
head(df_scaled2, 7)


opar <- par() 
# Define settings for plotting in a 3x4 grid, with appropriate margins:
par(mar = rep(0.8,4))
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
# Produce a radar-chart for each student
for (i in 4:nrow(df_scaled2)) {
  radarchart(
    df_scaled2[c(1:3, i), ],
    pfcol = c("#99999980",NA),
    pcol= c(NA,2), plty = 1, plwd = 2,
    title = row.names(df_scaled2)[i]
  )
}
# Restore the standard par() settings
par <- par(opar)
